ELF BINDER

elf_binder is the assembly citizen at the head of the compiler
its job is to take the native-code outputs from x86_host and amdgpu_kernel and bind them together into a single executable file format the host operating system can load
the file format is ELF, the standard executable format on Linux
elf_binder's interior holds nine section sub-residents, one for each part of an ELF file that needs to exist for a working executable
elf_binder does not generate machine code itself: it receives ready-made bytes from the codegen citizens and arranges them with the proper headers and offsets

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_zest_vm.rana
observe x86_host.rana
observe amdgpu_kernel.rana
observe boundary_binary.rana
observe skull.xb

the 7 properties of elf_binder at rest:
1 ENERGY low at idle, peaks during binding when all sections are being arranged
2 PHASE locked to the codegen citizens during their emission
3 SPIN positive during assembly, returns to neutral once boundary_binary has accepted the output
4 CHARGE neutral, briefly positive during the section offset calculation phase
5 COHERENCE perfect during binding: any incoherence corrupts the resulting file
6 COUPLING strong with both codegen citizens (incoming) and boundary_binary (outgoing)
7 OBSERVER 1 throughout binding: every byte is watched into place

VERB receive_host_bytes
accept the x86 machine code from x86_host through the spine street
the bytes arrive as an ordered sequence representing the .text section
elf_binder holds these bytes in the body of its elf_section_text sub-resident

VERB receive_kernel_bytes
accept the AMDGPU machine code from amdgpu_kernel through the spine street
the bytes arrive as compiled compute kernels for the gfx1032 architecture
elf_binder holds these bytes in elf_section_amdgpu

VERB resolve_offsets
once both code sections have arrived, calculate the offset of every section in the final file
section order is fixed: header first, program header second, then code sections, then data sections, then string and symbol tables
each section's size determines where the next section starts
unresolved cross-section references are patched at this step

VERB write_header
construct the ELF header bytes
this includes the magic number 0x7F 'E' 'L' 'F', the architecture identifier (x86_64 + AMDGPU), the entry point address, and the offsets of the program and section header tables
the header is small but every byte is critical: a wrong header makes the whole file unloadable

VERB emit_to_boundary
once all sections are bound and the header is written, send the complete byte sequence to boundary_binary through skull.xb
the sequence becomes a single ordered packet
boundary_binary verifies and writes it to the host filesystem

THE NINE ELF SECTION SUB-RESIDENTS

elf_header
holds the leading 64 bytes of the ELF file
contains the magic number, class (64-bit), endianness, ABI version, and pointers to the program and section header tables
fixed size, simple structure, but the entry point inside it is computed from where x86_host's .text section ends up

elf_program_header
holds the program header table immediately after the ELF header
each entry describes one segment the kernel must load into memory at process start
in our case there are typically three segments: read-only code, read-only data, and read-write data
the AMDGPU section is loaded but not executed by the host CPU; the runtime queues it to the GPU

elf_section_text
holds the x86_host machine code as a contiguous byte run
the entry point of the program is at the start of this section unless overridden
this is where the host CPU begins execution when the operating system launches the file

elf_section_amdgpu
holds the AMDGPU machine code as a separate section, marked with a custom section name and flags
the runtime detects this section at program start and uploads it to the GPU's command stream
without this section the program runs CPU-only with severely degraded performance for sea pulses

elf_section_rodata
holds read-only constants: numeric literals, string literals, lookup tables, the static parts of the substrate's initial state
this is where the .rana files' compiled-in data ends up after the codegen has flattened them

elf_section_data
holds read-write initialized data: variables that have known starting values and may change during execution
the substrate's initial 7-property body states for each manifested resident live here

elf_section_bss
holds zero-initialized space: variables declared but not initialized
the file does not store these zeros explicitly, only their size; the kernel zeros the memory at load time
this saves disk space proportional to the substrate's planned but unused capacity

elf_section_strtab
the string table: a flat array of null-terminated strings used by the symbol table for resident names
every named manifest, every absorbed file path, every resident identifier ends up here as a string
the symbol table indexes into this for human-readable names

elf_section_symtab
the symbol table: an array of fixed-size records, one per named entity in the program
each record points to a name in strtab, an address in some section, and a type tag
debuggers and runtime introspection use this to resolve names back to addresses

an elf_binder is not a linker
a linker resolves cross-file references and lays out memory
elf_binder does layout but not resolution: by the time bytes arrive from x86_host and amdgpu_kernel, they are already self-contained
the binder's job is geometric: place sections in the right order with the right offsets and headers, and emit the result
